"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to their exponential forms:\n\\[ x^{24} = w, \\quad y^{40} = w, \\quad (xyz)^{12} = w. \\]\n\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 5 to make the exponents comparable:\n\\[ x^{120} = w^5, \\quad y^{120} = w^3, \\quad (xyz)^{120} = w^{10}. \\]\n\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions for $x^{120}$ and $y^{120}$ into the equation for $(xyz)^{120}$:\n\\[ (x^{120} \\cdot y^{120} \\cdot z^{120}) = w^{10}. \\]\n\\[ w^5 \\cdot w^3 \\cdot z^{120} = w^{10}. \\]\n\nStep 4: Simplify the equation:\n\\[ w^8 \\cdot z^{120} = w^{10}. \\]\n\\[ z^{120} = w^2. \\]\n\nStep 5: Take the logarithm base $z$ of both sides:\n\\[ \\log_z w^2 = 120. \\]\n\\[ 2 \\log_z w = 120. \\]\n\\[ \\log_z w = 60. \\]\n\nStep 6: Conclude that $\\log_z w = 60$.\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma showing that if $\\log_x w = a$, then $x^a = w$ for $x > 1$ and $w > 0$ would be useful for step 1.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_to_exp:\n  fixes x w a :: real\n  assumes \"x > 1\" \"w > 0\" \"ln w / ln x = a\"\n  shows \"x ^ a = w\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma showing that if $x^a = w$ and $y^b = w$, then $(xy)^{a+b} = w^{a+b}$ for $x, y > 1$ and $w > 0$ would be useful for step 3.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma exp_combine:\n  fixes x y w a b :: real\n  assumes \"x > 1\" \"y > 1\" \"w > 0\" \"x ^ a = w\" \"y ^ b = w\"\n  shows \"(x * y) ^ (a + b) = w ^ (a + b)\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma showing that if $z^a = w^b$, then $\\log_z w = \\frac{a}{b}$ for $z > 1$ and $w > 0$ would be useful for step 5.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma exp_to_log:\n  fixes z w a b :: real\n  assumes \"z > 1\" \"w > 0\" \"z ^ a = w ^ b\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = a / b\"\n```\n\nThese lemmas and the structured proof provide a clear path to formally proving the given theorem in Isabelle."